## 4. SCSS Rules

### Slide sizing

Use `slidesPerView: 'auto'` in JS and set slide width via SCSS (all rules nested inside `.{slug}-section`):

```scss
.{slug}-section {
	.slide {
		inline-size: fluid(280, 400);  // responsive slide width
		max-inline-size: 95%;
	}
}
```

### Flex/grid parent fix

If the `.swiper` sits inside a flex or grid container, add:

```scss
.{slug}-section {
	.{slug}-slider {
		min-inline-size: 0;
	}
}
```

Without this, `min-inline-size: auto` prevents the slider from shrinking and breaks scrolling.

### Navigation styling (DO NOT redefine in block SCSS)

Global navigation styles live in `src/sass/partials/template-parts/_swiper-navigation.scss`. The `template-parts/swiper-navigation.php` template part outputs the `.swiper-navigation` wrapper, the `.swiper-button-prev` / `.swiper-button-next` elements, and the SVG arrows already styled.

Default look provided globally:
- 40×40px buttons with `all: unset` base
- Disabled state: `opacity: 0.5; pointer-events: none`
- Hover micro-animations on SVG arrows (`micro-left` / `micro-right` keyframes)
- Style variants via the `style` arg: `'floating'` → `.style-floating` (absolute), `'dark'` → `.style-dark`

If your design needs different colors (border, fill, hover bg), override **only the color properties** inside `.{slug}-section .swiper-navigation { … }` in the block SCSS. Never re-declare sizing, layout, base reset, gap, or hover animations.

### Pagination styling (DO NOT redefine in block SCSS)

Global pagination styles live in `src/sass/partials/template-parts/_swiper-pagination.scss`. The `template-parts/swiper-pagination.php` template part outputs the pagination element with the `swiper-pagination-line` class by default (equal-width bars). The directional-fill animation triggered by `data-direction` is wired up globally for both `.swiper-pagination-line` and `.swiper-pagination-dot`.

Available pagination shapes (all defined globally — just use the matching class via the template part or add it to the wrapper):

| Class                    | Look                | Defined in                          |
| ------------------------ | ------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `swiper-pagination-line` | Equal-width bars    | `_swiper-pagination.scss` (default) |
| `swiper-pagination-dot`  | Circular dots       | `_swiper-pagination.scss`           |
| `swiper-scrollbar`       | Draggable scrollbar | `_swiper-custom.scss`               |

If your design needs different colors, override **only the bullet colors** inside `.{slug}-section`:

```scss
.{slug}-section {
	.swiper-pagination-line .swiper-pagination-bullet {
		background-color: $your-track-color;

		&::after {
			background-color: $your-fill-color; // active fill
		}
	}
}
```

Never re-declare flex layout, gap, height, border-radius, position, opacity, or the directional `::after` transition rules — those are global.

### Directional animation

Forward/backward fill animation is already wired globally for `.swiper-pagination-line`, `.swiper-pagination-dot`, and `.swiper-scrollbar`.

How it works:

- Forward swipe: active bullet fills **left → right**, previous bullet empties **right → left**
- Backward swipe: directions reverse
- The JS `snapIndexChange` handler sets `data-direction` on the pagination/scrollbar container (see §2)
- The handler is bound on the Swiper instance **after** init, not in the config `on` object
- The CSS reacts via attribute selectors like `.swiper-pagination[data-direction='forward'] .swiper-pagination-bullet-active::after { … }` — already in `_swiper-pagination.scss`

### Custom overrides

The only block-specific swiper styling allowed is **color theming** of the existing pagination bullets and nav buttons. Sizing, layout, animation, and base resets always come from the global partials. If a design genuinely needs a different shape, extend the global partial with a new modifier class — do not redefine the existing classes inside a block.

